'''Dino Cinel''' was an Italian-American [[historian]], and a Distinguished Professor of Italian-American Studies at [[City University of New York]].<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb1367/is_199311/ai_n6389033/ "The porn prof on trial.", ''The Nation,'' November, 1993, Jon Wiener ]</ref>
==Life== In 1988, he was a Roman Catholic priest at St. Rita's Church, [[New Orleans]]. He was investigated over his possession of homosexual child [[pornography]].<ref>[http://www.bishop-accountability.org/news5/1991_12_Bennetts_UnholyAlliances.htm "Unholy Alliances", ''Vanity Fair'', Leslie Bennetts, December 1991]</ref> He sued over the public release of the information.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.romingerlegal.com/fifthcircuit/opinions/92-03781.CV0.wpd.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927173355/http://www.romingerlegal.com/fifthcircuit/opinions/92-03781.CV0.wpd.html |archivedate=2011-09-27 |df= }}</ref>
He taught at [[Tulane University]]. The scholarship of his book, ''From Italy to San Francisco'', has been questioned.<ref>[http://hnn.us/articles/1420.html "The Disturbing Case of Dino Cinel", ''History News Network'', Sebastian Fichera, 4-28-03]</ref><ref>[http://hnn.us/comments/11900.html "Dino Cinel", ''History News Network'', Andrew M. Canepa, May 7, 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041124173435/http://hnn.us/comments/11900.html |date=November 24, 2004 }}</ref>
Cinel was stabbed to death in Medellin, Colombia in February 2018 by an 18-year-old man with whom he had been in a relationship.
