{{orphan|date=April 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Judith Ann Bennett | native_name = Judy Bennett | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1944<!-- {{Birth date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | other_names = | residence = New Zealand | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = | patrons = | alma_mater = [[Australian National University]] | thesis1_title = Wealth of the Solomons : a history of trade, plantations and society, Solomon Islands, c.1800–1942 | thesis1_url = https://library.anu.edu.au/record=b1235279 | thesis1_year = 1979 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = | children = }} '''Judith Ann Bennett''' (born 1944) is a New Zealand historian. She is currently a full professor at the [[University of Otago]].<ref name="bio">{{cite web|url=https://www.otago.ac.nz/historyarthistory/staff/otago035982.html |title=Professor Judy Bennett, Our People, Department of History and Art History, University of Otago, New Zealand |publisher=Otago.ac.nz |date=30 March 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>
==Academic career==
Bennett wrote a 1979 [[PhD]] thesis at [[Australian National University]] titled, '' 'Wealth of the Solomons: a history of trade, plantations and society, Solomon Islands, c.1800–1942' ''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://library.anu.edu.au/record=b1235279 |title=Australian National University |publisher=Library.anu.edu.au |date= |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> studying the colonial history of the [[Solomon Islands]] and has spent much of her career researching, writing and teaching about the Pacific and its history.
Bennett has received two Marsden grants, the first to research the children of American servicemen and pacific women<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spasifikmag.com/communityhealth/29junebreakingsilencegibabies/ |title=Breaking Silence: GI Babies and their Pasifika Mothers |publisher=Spasifikmag.com |date= |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rudd |first=Allison |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/pacific-children-us-servicemen-study |title=Pacific children of US servicemen for study &#124; Otago Daily Times Online News |publisher=Odt.co.nz |date=5 January 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Elder |first=Vaughan |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/tears-flow-story-war-babies |title=Tears flow for story of war babies &#124; Otago Daily Times Online News |publisher=Odt.co.nz |date=26 November 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> and the second to research the history of the coconut and its trade.<ref name="bio"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.otago.ac.nz/crocc/tag/judy-bennett/ |title=Judy Bennett &#124; Centre for Research on Colonial Culture |publisher=Blogs.otago.ac.nz |date= |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=11386326 |title=Q&A: All you needed to know about the humble coconut |publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date= |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>
